WÅ‚adysÅ‚aw JÃ³zef Marian Turowicz23 April 1908 â€“ 8 January 1980), usually referred to as W. J. M. Turowicz, was a Polish-Pakistani aviator, military scientist and aeronautical engineer. text:
The was a PAF flight officer named Mervyn Leslie Middlecoat. He fought in the 1965 conflict with India. During the 1967 Arab - Israeli war he formed part of a  contingent of Pakistani pilots who volunteered to fly for the participating Arab states. Mervyn was sent to Jordan. Later on Middlecoat was KIA during the 1971 war.

Incidently, the legendary Saif ul Azam, flew for both Iraq and also Jordan. He was credited with shooting down 4 Israeli jets, in total. During the 1965 he had shot down at least 1 indian aeroplane. Sadly, due to being of Bengali origin, Saif ul Azam was not permitted to fight during the tragic 1971 war. Soon after he went to the new state of Bangladesh, where he held prominent and senior positions in both military and civil aviation. He died in Dhaka in 2020, mourned by many, including numerous senior PAF officers.

Another PAF pilot of Bengali origin, M.M Alam became an extremely rare 'Ace in a day' when he shot down FIVE indian planes in a couple of minutes during the 1965 war. Again, ashamedly, Alam, due to being of Bengali heritage was denied permission to fly during the 1971 war. 'Little Dragon' as he was affectionately known, remained loyal to Pakistan, living in Karachi until his death in 2013.

Salute and respect to the brave PAF pilot, Kamran Bashir.

Our heartfelt prayers are with his parents, regardless of their religious background.

As a society, we tend to admire heroes when they succeedâ€”standing beside them in moments of glory. Yet, when they face challenges, true support is often lacking. This tendency exists among both Muslims and non-Muslims, though, regrettably, it is sometimes more pronounced towards non-Muslimism. The story and struggles of javelin athlete and Olympic gold medalist Arshad Nadeem are a good example of this tendency.

If we truly follow the teachings of the Quran and the Sunnah, we must uphold the dignity and rights of people from all religions on merit. Sadly, as a Pakistani and a Muslim, I acknowledge with a heavy heart that there are extremist elements within our society who exploit religious divisions for political gain. This is wrong and must be condemned and stopped at every level.

Time will tell whether this pilotâ€”Kamran Bashirâ€”will rise through the ranks on merit to become an Air Vice Marshal or Air Marshal. When that time comes, it will reflect not only on his abilities but also on the fairness and inclusiveness of our institutions and society.

Â @IlmGems06Â  "When (the following) was revealed: 'Alif Lam Mim. The Romans have been defeated. In the nearest land, and they, after their defeat, will be victorious in Bid' years (30:1-4).' - on the day that these Ayat were revealed, the Persians had defeated the Romans, and the Muslims had wanted the Romans to be victorious over them, because they were the people of the Book. So Allah said about that: 'And on that day, the believers will rejoice - with the help of Allah. He helps whom He wills, and He is the Almighty, the Most Merciful (30:4 & 5). The Quraish wanted the Persians to be victorious since they were not people of the Book, nor did they believe in the Resurrection. So when Allah revealed these Ayat, Abu Bakr As-Siddiq, may Allah be pleased with him, went out, proclaiming throughout Makkah: 'Alif Lam Mim. The Romans have been defeated. In the nearest land, and they, after their defeat, will be victorious, in Bid' years (30:1-4).' Some of the Quraish said: 'Then this is (a bet) between us and you. Your companion claims that the Romans will defeat the Persians in Bid' years, so why have have a bet on that between us and you?' Abu Bakr said: 'Yes.' This was before betting has been forbidden. So Abu Bakr and the idolaters made a bet, and they said to Abu Bakr: 'What do you think - Bid' means something between three and nine years, so let us agree on the middle.' So they agreed on six years; Then six years passed without the Romans being victorious. The idolaters took what they won in the bet from Abu Bakr. When the seventh year came and the Romans were finally victorious over the Persians, the Muslims rebuked Abu Bakr for agreeing to six years. He said: 'Because Allah said: 'In Bid' years.' At that time, many people became Muslims."

text: Â @kamekameha721Â  the idea that Kashmir belongs to India simply because it had a Hindu population at one point ignores both historical continuity and demographic evolution. The current Muslim majority in Kashmir are not outsiders; they are likely the descendants of the very same people who once practiced Hinduism but gradually converted to Islam over centuries, particularly during the spread of Islam in the region from the 14th century onward. This means the Kashmiri people have remained rooted to their land throughout history â€” their identity has evolved, but their connection to the land has not changed. On the other hand, many of the modern Hindus claiming ancestral ties to Kashmir come from other regions of India and have no direct historical or cultural link to the land or its people. Thus, using ancient religious demographics to justify political control ignores the lived reality and rights of the people who have continuously inhabited Kashmir for generations.

text:
There was a PAF flight officer named Mervyn Leslie Middlecoat. He fought in the 1965 conflict with India. During the 1967 Arab - Israeli war, he formed part of a contingent of Pakistani pilots who volunteered to fly for the participating Arab states. Mervyn was sent to Jordan. Later on, Middlecoat was KIA during the 1971 war. 
Incidently, the legendary Saif ul Azam flew for both Iraq and Jordan. He was credited with shooting down 4 Israeli jets in total. During 1965, he had shot down at least 1 indian aeroplane. Sadly, due to being of Bengali origin, Saif ul Azam was not permitted to fight during the tragic 1971 war. Soon after, he went to the new state of Bangladesh, where he held prominent and senior positions in both military and civil aviation. He died in Dhaka in 2020, mourned by many, including numerous senior PAF officers. 
Another PAF pilot of Bengali origin, M.M Alam, became an extremely rare 'Ace in a day' when he shot down FIVE indian planes in a couple of minutes during the 1965 war. Again, ashamedly, Alam, due to being of Bengali heritage, was denied permission to fly during the 1971 war. 'Little Dragon' as he was affectionately known, remained loyal to Pakistan, living in Karachi until his death in 2013.
